I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU. We're seeing a slow RAM exhaustion issue where the heap usage creeps up by about 15KB every 2-3 hours of operation. It's not crashing immediately, but it hits the limit mid-drive. I've looked at the main loops, but I can't find the culprit. 

Can you give me a systematic approach or a list of specific things to check in this snippet to track down where the allocation isn't being freed?

```cpp
void process_sensor_data(const SensorPacket* packet) {
    if (packet == nullptr) return;

    // Allocate buffer for processing
    uint8_t* processing_buffer = new uint8_t[MAX_BUFFER_SIZE];

    if (validate_packet(packet)) {
        copy_to_buffer(packet->data, processing_buffer, packet->size);
        calculate_checksum(processing_buffer, packet->size);
        update_ecu_state(processing_buffer);
    } else {
        log_error("Invalid packet received");
    }

    // I think I'm handling the cleanup here, but the leak persists
    delete[] processing_buffer;
}

void system_loop() {
    while (system_running) {
        SensorPacket* incoming = sensor_interface.poll();
        if (incoming) {
            process_sensor_data(incoming);
            // Note: sensor_interface.poll() returns a pointer 
            // that needs to be managed elsewhere or here
        }
        wait_for_next_tick();
    }
}
```

